text: It's astounding really how many people will complain without at least fact-checking. Like sure, you don't have to actually see the movies to have a gripe, but before you complain at least know what you're talking about?  1.) Only a certain level of government official is exempt. Not all. Otherwise anyone would be vying to become any kind of government official, and you don't hear a lot of people praying the mayor dies soon so they can try for their job.  2.) "This is so stupid. One day a year of free crime wouldn't stop crime from happening the rest of the year!" Exactly. This is literally the point of the movie series. It's not /about/ ending crime, it's about the government giving people a license to kill what they consider the "Undesirables", as more or less assured by the prejudices they establish in the country. The poor, for instance, have been THE MAIN target in both movies. And they even show how that coincides with the racial intolerance of the country. They keep POC down by denying jobs, paying less, etc. So they have less money. So they have less chance of defending themselves. It's a commentary on greed and white supremacy in our government and among people in power, and how both mean that "pre established laws" aren't above questioning by the oppressed.  3.) "Americans WOULD love to murder their neighbors. Not surprised." another fallacy. As revealed in Purge 2, most people AREN'T killing. Especially in the mid to lower class. They're doing other crimes, if any, and it was implied by tone that they're probably petty ones. So the government has been using planted people to kill and to further encourage the Purge.  ^Those three points cover and dismiss most of the complaints in this comment section, and they were MAIN points that weren't hard to miss or look up. That's how much people don't bother to fact check before complaining. Honestly...

text: 'Why do they wear masks if everything is legal?" Well if you committed crimes without a mask, the victim or the victim's friends and/or family could track you down and come after you the next purge. Also, wearing a terrifying or creepy mask generally gives off the vibe that you're dangerous and/or crazy, ergo people a less likely to mess with you. Also, what's more threatening and terrifying: a random guy with an unknown face chasing you? Or a random guy in a Bugs Bunny costume chasing you?

text: I sometimes wish the Purge movies would explore different aspects of crime than just murder. Not EVERYONE would go out and kill someone, there are people who would see the purge as a opportunity to steal things like the newest ps4 or xbox, movies, food, money etc.  Yes, murderous psychopaths as shown in these films exist and there would definitely be murders on Purge night but it seems like that's the only aspect of crime that's out there in these films and the longer this series goes on, it will eventually run out of steam and become boring. There are other thongs people would do on a free night like this. Steal, murder, deal illegal drugs publicly.. other things or just stay at home.. It would be interesting if a purge film had three story arcs on three different sets of people doing different things on Purge night. One story arc would follow a group of (likable) psychopaths going on a murder spree (murder aspect), another story arc have a group of people or teenagers having fun going around the city stealing things (robbery aspect) and another have a family just trying to survive the night at home when a group of angry druggies try to break in and kill them because the husband who secretly has a drug problem has been secretly buying drugs from them and still owes their money. (illegal drugs aspect)  I don't know something different, rather than the same things happening every film: Showing characters who need to survive a world of raving maniacs killing people left and right for no reason. This would bring a breath of fresh air to the franchise if it ever were to continue. But looks like its trying to be the last.. but that's the thing about Hollywood, you never know which one is truly the last film in a successful franchise.

"Keep America Great" seems to indicate that this is what America would look like if Trump were allowed to Make America Great Again. "The Purge targets the poor and homeless" refers to Trump's policies, and the movie centers around the upper class and ruling members of both political parties being underhanded and going against the will of the public, something we've seen a lot of in this election so far.

text: ALL crime is legal, huh? What if, on the Purge night, an entire revolution was undertaken? What if revolutionary thinkers, like the fictional Tyler Durdin with his Project Mayhem from "Fight Club," decided to burn down the important government buildings and bomb the financial hubs of Wall Street? What if military operatives collectively went rogue and killed all of the important leading officials? What if the people with passwords to the weapons of mass destruction accessed the bombs that would annihilate entire civilizations? What if the Purge never ended because there would be no one to mandate the end of anarchy? What if anarchy persisted because no government existed? Wouldn't that be something terrible. This is why I do not condone this movie's plot line. I like our society the way we built it. It is imperfect, but so be it. I would not want a Purge day.

text: What I find interesting about the Purge franchise, is that the society the New Founding Fathers of America created is a far more authoritarian and fatalistic one. The Purge happens one night every year, and supposedly it helps eliminate crime, poverty and social unrest. So that everyone is far better off.  The initial vision of the Purge may have been extreme but it probably did help the country survive whatever calamity the U.S was going through. But like all things born of power it gets corrupted. The Purge releases the worst of humanity to act out every sick and twisted desire with impunity. Releasing the Beast as the people call it is supposed to help society get all their frustration and rage out in one night. People who kill and like it don't just stop, they want more. People are no doubt counting down the days to the next Purge. The New Founding Fathers intentionally or unintentionally are breeding a nation of killers and psychopaths. But they remain in power, so of course the dont want anyone to threaten that. So that's why Elizabeth Mitchell's character is big target in the third film. I should check these films out, while not perfect the Purge Films remind me of George Romero's works, gory horror married with social commentary.
